            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <p>Overseas advertising campaigns across platforms like Meta, TikTok, and Google often face reconciliation headaches: discrepancies between top-up debits and platform bills, mismatched consumption data, and complex invoice processes. These issues accumulate quickly, especially with multi-account management, leading to financial risks.</p>
<p>This article breaks down the three core areas—top-up verification, consumption reconciliation, and invoice validation—into actionable checklists to help teams establish standardized reconciliation SOPs.</p>
<h2>1. Top-Up Verification Checklist</h2>
<p><strong>For each top-up transaction, verify the following:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Top-up amount matches the bank debit record (account for timezone and exchange rate differences)</li>
<li>[ ] Top-up timestamp aligns with when the balance appeared in the account</li>
<li>[ ] Top-up account ID correctly corresponds to the ad account ID</li>
<li>[ ] Top-up proof (screenshots or bank statements) is archived</li>
<li>[ ] For multi-account top-ups, clearly label which account each top-up belongs to</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>⚠️ Common Issue:</strong> Balance not credited after top-up? Two common causes: platform processing delay (usually 1-2 hours) or payment channel limits causing the debit to fail. Keep payment proof and contact platform support promptly.</p>
<h2>2. Consumption Reconciliation Checklist</h2>
<h3>Daily Checks</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Export daily consumption report and cross-verify with financial system records</li>
<li>[ ] Confirm all account balances are sufficient to avoid campaign interruptions</li>
<li>[ ] Log daily consumption data and monitor for unusual fluctuations</li>
</ul>
<h3>Weekly Checks</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Compare weekly consumption with the same period last week to identify anomalies</li>
<li>[ ] Verify top-up amounts versus total consumption to confirm reasonable balance levels</li>
<li>[ ] Check whether consumption changes align with budget adjustments</li>
</ul>
<h3>Monthly Checks</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Generate monthly consumption reports and aggregate platform data</li>
<li>[ ] Reconcile monthly consumption with invoice amounts</li>
<li>[ ] Analyze per-account CAC or CPA trends to identify underperforming accounts</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>💡 Tip:</strong> If an account shows significantly lower or higher consumption, first check for platform policy restrictions or budget configuration errors.</p>
<h2>3. Invoice Validation Process</h2>
<p><strong>After receiving invoices, validate step by step:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>[ ] <strong>Information Check:</strong> Invoice title and tax ID match company registration details</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Amount Check:</strong> Invoice amount matches net consumption for the billing period (after deducting refunds)</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Element Verification:</strong> Invoice code, number, and date are complete</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Authenticity Check:</strong> Verify through local tax authority or platform-provided verification portal</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Archiving:</strong> Link the invoice with corresponding period top-up records and consumption reports</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>⚠️ Notes:</strong><br />
- Billing cycles vary by platform: Meta typically invoices monthly, while TikTok may require proactive application<br />
- Some platforms support e-invoices directly usable for expense reporting<br />
- If invoice errors are found, request a reissue within 30 days of issuance</p>
<h2>4. Multi-Platform Reconciliation Best Practices</h2>
<p>When managing multiple ad platforms:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Standardize Billing Cycles:</strong> Recommend using calendar months consistently across all platforms</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Create Summary Reports:</strong> Build consolidated consumption reports for easy cross-platform comparison</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Separate Ledgers:</strong> Maintain individual ledgers per platform tracking top-ups, consumption, and balance flow</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Define Exchange Rate Rules:</strong> For multi-currency situations, agree on consistent exchange rate sources and conversion timestamps</li>
</ul>
<h2>5. Quick Reference: Common Issues</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Issue</th>
<th>Possible Cause</th>
<th>Recommended Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Bill amount doesn't match backend consumption</td>
<td>Timezone differences, unprocessed refunds, different attribution windows</td>
<td>Compare report periods, check refund records</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Invoice amount less than consumption</td>
<td>Partial consumption not yet reconciled, promotional credits deducted</td>
<td>Verify against billing details</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Balance not increased after top-up</td>
<td>Payment failed, platform processing delay</td>
<td>Check bank statements, contact platform with proof</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Invoice application rejected</td>
<td>Incorrect information, mismatched billing entity</td>
<td>Verify correct details and resubmit</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />
<p><strong>Core reconciliation principle: unified data sources, consistent definitions, and timely documentation.</strong> Whether it's top-ups, consumption, or invoices—archive original records for every step to enable future verification. By consistently following this checklist, teams can significantly reduce financial reconciliation errors and focus more energy on optimizing campaign performance.</p>
